06004nam a22008415i 9780812296785DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20182019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122967857 a10.9783/97808122967852doi  a(DE-B1597)514585  a(OCoLC)1078996211  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aJC489 7aPOL0620002bisacsh04a327.12732231 aWillard-Foster, Melissa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aToppling Foreign Governments :bThe Logic of Regime Change /cMelissa Willard-Foster. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2018] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b8 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Why the Strong Impose Regime Change on the Weak -- tChapter 2. How States Impose Regime Change -- tChapter 3. Testing the Logic of Foreign-Imposed Regime Change -- tChapter 4. The Cold War: American Policy Toward Bolivia and Guatemala, 1952–54 -- tChapter 5. The Cold War: Soviet Policy Toward Poland and Hungary, 1956 -- tChapter 6. The Post-9/11 Era: Regime Change and Rogues, Iraq 2003, Libya 2003, and Libya 2011 -- tConclusion -- tAppendix 1. Foreign-Imposed Regime Change, 1816–2007 -- tAppendix 2. A Game Theoretic Model of Regime Change -- tNOTES -- tINDEX -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2011, the United States launched its third regime-change attempt in a decade. Like earlier targets, Libya's Muammar Qaddafi had little hope of defeating the forces stacked against him. He seemed to recognize this when calling for a cease-fire just after the intervention began. But by then, the United States had determined it was better to oust him than negotiate and thus backed his opposition. The history of foreign-imposed regime change is replete with leaders like Qaddafi, overthrown after wars they seemed unlikely to win. From the British ouster of Afghanistan's Sher Ali in 1878 to the Soviet overthrow of Hungary's Imre Nagy in 1956, regime change has been imposed on the weak and the friendless.In Toppling Foreign Governments, Melissa Willard-Foster explores the question of why stronger nations overthrow governments when they could attain their aims at the bargaining table. She identifies a central cause—the targeted leader's domestic political vulnerability—that not only gives the leader motive to resist a stronger nation's demands, making a bargain more difficult to attain, but also gives the stronger nation reason to believe that regime change will be comparatively cheap. As long as the targeted leader's domestic opposition is willing to collaborate with the foreign power, the latter is likely to conclude that ousting the leader is more cost effective than negotiating.Willard-Foster analyzes 133 instances of regime change, ranging from covert operations to major military invasions, and spanning over two hundred years. She also conducts three in-depth case studies that support her contention that domestically and militarily weak leaders appear more costly to coerce than overthrow and, as long as they remain ubiquitous, foreign-imposed regime change is likely to endure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aInternational relationsxResearchxMathematical models. 0aIntervention (International law)xGovernment policyzSoviet UnionvCase studies. 0aIntervention (International law)xGovernment policyzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aRegime changevCase studies. 0aRegime changexGovernment policyzSoviet UnionvCase studies. 0aRegime changexGovernment policyzUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Geopolitics.2bisacsh  aMilitary Science.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.